\f0 \cf2 Figure Legends (Nature Reviews Gastroenterology & Hepatology style)
\f1\fs53\fsmilli26667 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa106\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf2 \cb6 Figure 1 | The postoperative immune\'96ecological remodelling window (PIERW)
\f1\fs42\fsmilli21333 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf3 \cb6 Ileocolonic resection removes macroscopic inflammatory lesions but initiates a finite period of biological instability during which microbial recolonisation, epithelial repair and mucosal immune reprogramming collectively shape long-term disease trajectory. Within the postoperative immune\'96ecological remodelling window (PIERW; approximately 0\'966 months after surgery), bidirectional interactions among microbiome dynamics, barrier remodelling and immune activation determine whether the neoterminal ileum progresses towards immune homeostasis or recurrent inflammation. Nutritional interventions (exclusive enteral nutrition (EEN), partial enteral nutrition (PEN) and Crohn\'92s disease exclusion diet (CDED)), biologics and AI-enabled surveillance may redirect this remodelling process before irreversible structural recurrence develops. Failed remodelling results in persistent dysbiosis, barrier dysfunction, transmural inflammation and repeat surgery.
\f2 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa106\partightenfactor0

\f0 \cf2 Figure 1 | The three biological phenotypes of the postoperative immune\'96ecological remodelling window (PIERW)
\f1\fs42\fsmilli21333 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf3 After ileocolonic resection, the neoterminal ileum may undergo divergent remodelling trajectories that influence recurrence risk and therapeutic responsiveness. Barrier-dominant PIERW (teal) is characterised by epithelial permeability, tight-junction disruption and depletion of butyrate-producing commensals, potentially favouring ecological and gut-selective therapeutic strategies. Immune-dominant PIERW (amber) is associated with amplified Th1/Th17 signalling, mesenteric inflammation and systemic immune activation, supporting prioritisation of cytokine-directed therapy. Fibrosis-dominant PIERW (purple) is characterised by mesenchymal activation, extracellular matrix remodelling and progressive structural change, suggesting a role for intensive structural surveillance and future anti-fibrotic approaches. The taxonomy proposes that postoperative prevention should be aligned to dominant remodelling biology rather than applied uniformly across patients.
\f2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa106\partightenfactor0

\f0 \cf2 Refined Figure 2 legend (NRGH tone)
\f1\fs53\fsmilli26667 \

\f0\fs32 Figure 2 | The Stratify\'96Adapt\'96Dynamic (SAD) platform architecture during the postoperative immune\'96ecological remodelling window
\f1\fs42\fsmilli21333 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf3 Patients undergoing ileocolonic resection are stratified into barrier-dominant, immune-dominant and fibrosis-dominant phenotypes using integrated molecular profiling, microbiome analysis and AI-assisted histopathology. Within each biological stratum, participants undergo mechanism-matched randomisation. Longitudinal Bayesian monitoring integrates intestinal ultrasound, biomarker trajectories and AI-assisted endoscopy to support dynamic treatment adaptation during postoperative remodelling. Trial endpoints span biological, patient-centred and systems-level domains, enabling simultaneous evaluation of mechanistic efficacy, behavioural sustainability and health-system impact.
\f2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0 \cf3 \'a0
\f2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa106\partightenfactor0

\f0 \cf2 Figure 2 | Stratify\'96adapt\'96dynamic (SAD) framework for precision postoperative management
\f1\fs42\fsmilli21333 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf3 A dynamic precision-prevention framework integrating multimodal baseline stratification, adaptive surveillance and mechanism-matched intervention after ileocolonic resection. Clinical phenotype, surgical pathology, transcriptomics, microbiome composition, inflammatory biomarkers and AI-enhanced imaging feed into a continuously updated prediction engine. Patients transition dynamically between immune-quiescent, barrier/ecology-dominant and immune-aggressive trajectories rather than remaining within fixed risk categories. Continuous monitoring through home biomarkers, intestinal ultrasound and AI-assisted endoscopy enables real-time recalibration of recurrence risk and treatment adaptation. The framework reframes postoperative management from static prophylaxis towards longitudinal trajectory control.
\f2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0 \cf3 \'a0
\f2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa106\partightenfactor0

\f0 \cf2 Figure 3 | Reframing enteral nutrition from supportive care to ecosystem engineering
\f1\fs42\fsmilli21333 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs32 \cf3 Western dietary exposure after surgery promotes dysbiosis, epithelial permeability and inflammatory amplification, thereby destabilising postoperative remodelling. By contrast, enteral nutrition-based strategies reshape the postoperative ecosystem through microbiome restoration, metabolic normalisation and barrier repair. Exclusive enteral nutrition (EEN), partial enteral nutrition (PEN), Crohn\'92s disease exclusion diet (CDED)-based approaches and biologic\'96nutrition combination strategies differ in ecological potency and behavioural sustainability. The therapeutic value of nutritional therapy therefore derives not only from nutrient delivery but also from modulation of luminal ecology, microbial diversity and immune\'96barrier interactions.
\f2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0 \cf3 \'a0
\f2 \
