\f5\b\fs28 \cf3 Box 1 | Clinical vignettes illustrating postoperative immune\'96ecological remodelling window (PIERW) phenotypes
\f2\b0\fs32 \

\f5\b\fs28 Patient A | Barrier-dominant PIERW
\f2\b0\fs32 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs28 \cf3 A 28-year-old woman with inflammatory ileocolonic Crohn\'92s disease (B1 phenotype) undergoes first ileocolic resection with stapled side-to-side anastomosis. Before surgery, she achieved clinical remission with exclusive enteral nutrition (EEN). Histopathology demonstrates relatively preserved mucosal architecture with reduced occludin expression and minimal submucosal inflammatory infiltration. Microbiome profiling reveals low \uc0\u945 -diversity with depletion of 
\f6\i Faecalibacterium prausnitzii
\f0\i0 . At postoperative week 2, faecal calprotectin is modestly elevated (180 \uc0\u956 g g\u8315 \'b9) despite normal CRP concentrations and absence of systemic symptoms.
\f2\fs32 \

\f0\fs28 She is classified as having a barrier-dominant remodelling phenotype and receives vedolizumab combined with cyclical partial enteral nutrition (50% energy replacement). At 6 months, ileocolonoscopy demonstrates Rutgeerts i1 disease, and by 12 months she achieves deep biomarker remission with restoration of microbial diversity.
\f2\fs32 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f5\b\fs28 \cf3 Biological interpretation
\f2\b0\fs32 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs28 \cf3 Recurrence risk is driven primarily by epithelial dysfunction and ecological instability rather than systemic immune activation.
