\f5\b\fs28 \cf3 Patient C | Fibrosis-dominant PIERW
\f2\b0\fs32 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs28 \cf3 A 42-year-old man with recurrent stricturing jejunoileitis (B2 phenotype) presents with high-grade small-bowel obstruction requiring resection after multiple prior balloon dilations. Histology demonstrates extensive submucosal collagen deposition, elevated profibrotic transcriptomic markers (including 
\f6\i PLOD2
\f0\i0  and 
\f6\i ZFPM2
\f0\i0 ) and dense mast-cell accumulation around the myenteric plexus.
\f2\fs32 \

\f0\fs28 At postoperative month 3, intestinal ultrasound reveals anastomotic wall thickening with increased stiffness on shear-wave elastography despite minimal inflammatory biomarker elevation. He is classified as having a fibrosis-dominant remodelling phenotype and receives ustekinumab with intensive structural surveillance. Six-month endoscopy identifies early asymptomatic anastomotic stenosis requiring prophylactic balloon dilation. He remains surgery-free at 24 months.
\f2\fs32 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

